
Interview Questions

1) What is abstraction in Java? Explain with a real-world example.
-->Abstraction means hiding internal implementation details and showing only essential functionality to the user.
    
    Real-world example:
    
    When you drive a car, you use:
    
    steering
    brake
    accelerator
    
    You don’t know the complete internal engine mechanism.
    You only use the required features.
    
    In Java:
    
    Abstract class and interface are used to achieve abstraction.
    abstract class Vehicle {
        abstract void start();
    }
    
    class Car extends Vehicle {
        void start() {
            System.out.println("Car starts with key");
        }
    }
    

2) How is abstraction different from encapsulation?
-->
    | Abstraction                             | Encapsulation                                        |
    | --------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
    | Hides implementation details            | Hides data                                           |
    | Focuses on “what to do”                 | Focuses on “how to protect data”                     |
    | Achieved using abstract class/interface | Achieved using private variables and getters/setters |
    | Example: ATM machine operations         | Example: Bank account balance hidden                 |
    Simple line:
    Abstraction → Hiding complexity
    Encapsulation → Hiding data



3) How can you achieve abstraction in Java?
-->Java achieves abstraction using:
    
    1. Abstract Class
    Can contain:
    abstract methods
    normal methods
    abstract class Animal {
        abstract void sound();
    }
    2. Interface
    Used for complete abstraction (before Java 8)
    interface Animal {
        void sound();
    }
    

4) What is the difference between an interface and an abstract class (before Java 8 vs after Java 8)?
-->
| Feature              | Abstract Class    | Interface Before Java 8  | Interface After Java 8      |
| -------------------- | ----------------- | ------------------------ | --------------------------- |
| Methods              | Abstract + normal | Only abstract methods    | Abstract + default + static |
| Variables            | Any type          | public static final only | Same                        |
| Constructor          | Yes               | No                       | No                          |
| Multiple inheritance | No                | Yes                      | Yes                         |
| Access modifiers     | Any               | public only              | public only                 |
    Before Java 8:
        Interfaces only had abstract methods.
    
    After Java 8:
      Interfaces support:
          default methods
          static methods
    This was introduced to support backward compatibility.



5) Can an abstract class implement an interface?
-->Yes.
    An abstract class can implement an interface without providing implementation for all methods.

    When a normal (concrete) class implements an interface, it is mandatory to override and provide implementation for all abstract
    methods of that interface, otherwise the class must be declared abstract. However, overriding default methods is not mandatory 
    because they already contain implementation inside the interface. If an abstract class implements an interface, it is not compulsory 
    to override the interface methods because an abstract class is allowed to remain incomplete. Similarly, when one interface extends
    another interface, it is also not mandatory to implement or override the inherited methods, because interfaces only define method 
    declarations, and the responsibility of implementation is passed to the final concrete class.

    interface Test {
        void display();
    }
    
    abstract class Demo implements Test {
    }
    
    The subclass must implement the remaining methods.



6) What is abstract method?
-->An abstract method:
    
    has only declaration
    does not contain a body
    must be implemented by subclass
    abstract void show();
    
    Example:
    
    abstract class Shape {
        abstract void draw();
    }


7) If an abstract class contains a constructor, why are we still unable to create objects of an abstract class? Explain the reason behind having a constructor there?
-->Why object creation is not allowed:
    
    Abstract classes are incomplete because they may contain abstract methods without implementation.
    
    So Java prevents object creation.
    
    abstract class A {
        abstract void show();
    }
    A obj = new A(); // ERROR
    Then why constructor?
    
    Constructor is used for:
    
    initializing common variables
    constructor chaining
    
    When subclass object is created, parent abstract class constructor executes first.
    
    abstract class Animal {
        Animal() {
            System.out.println("Animal constructor");
        }
    }



8) Can we use default and static methods in an interface? Why were they introduced?
-->Yes.
    Default methods
    
    Allow method body inside interface.
    
    default void show() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
    Static methods
    static void display() {
        System.out.println("Static");
    }
    Why introduced?
    
    To maintain backward compatibility.
    
    Suppose an old interface is used by 100 classes.
    If a new method is added:
    
    all 100 classes would break.
    
    Default methods solve this problem.



9) What is marker interface? Name two examples?
-->A marker interface is an interface with no methods or variables.
    
    Used to provide special information to JVM.
    
    Examples:
    
    Serializable
    Cloneable
    
    Example:
    
    interface Test {
    }


10) Can an interface contain variables? What is their default nature?
-->Yes.
    All variables in an interface are automatically:
    
    public
    static
    final
    
    Example:
    
    interface Demo {
        int x = 10;
    }
    
    Actually Java treats it as:
    
    public static final int x = 10;


11) Explain Dynamic Method Dispatch in relation to abstraction?
-->Dynamic Method Dispatch means:
    
    method call is decided at runtime
    based on object type
    
    Example:
    
    abstract class Animal {
        abstract void sound();
    }
    
    class Dog extends Animal {
        void sound() {
            System.out.println("Bark");
        }
    }
    
    class Cat extends Animal {
        void sound() {
            System.out.println("Meow");
        }
    }
    
    public class Main {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Animal a;
    
            a = new Dog();
            a.sound();
    
            a = new Cat();
            a.sound();
        }
    }
    
    This supports:
    
    runtime polymorphism
    abstraction


12) If Java does not support multiple inheritance, how can a class implement multiple interfaces?
-->Java does not support multiple inheritance with classes because of the diamond problem.

    But interfaces only contain method declarations (before Java 8), so ambiguity does not occur.
    
    Example:
    
    interface A {
        void show();
    }
    
    interface B {
        void display();
    }
    
    class Test implements A, B {
    
        public void show() {
            System.out.println("Show");
        }
    
        public void display() {
            System.out.println("Display");
        }
    }

==> what is an concrete class in java?
-->A concrete class in Java is a standard class that has a complete implementation for all of its methods. Unlike abstract classes or 
    interfaces, a concrete class contains no unimplemented (abstract) methods, making it a fully functional blueprint that can be used 
    to create objects.
    Key CharacteristicsInstantiation: You can create instances (objects) of a concrete class using the new keyword.
    Method Implementation: Every method in the class must have a body (logic defined between {}).
    Inheritance: It can extend an abstract class or implement multiple interfaces, provided it gives a concrete implementation for every
    inherited abstract method.
    Modality: It is never declared with the abstract keyword. However, it can be declared as final if you want to prevent other classes 
    from extending it.


13) What happens when a subclass does not implement all abstract methods of its abstract parent class? Why does Java force this?
-->Then the subclass must also be declared abstract.
    
    abstract class A {
        abstract void show();
    }
    
    abstract class B extends A {
    }
    
    Otherwise compile-time error occurs.
    
    Why Java forces this?
    
    Because incomplete classes should not create objects.
    
    Java ensures:  every concrete class gives complete implementation.




14) Why do interfaces in Java (before Java 8) allow only public abstract methods? Explain logically.
-->Interfaces are used for:
    
    achieving complete abstraction
    defining a contract
    
    Methods must be:
    
    public → accessible everywhere
    abstract → implementation provided by subclass
    
    If methods were private/protected:
    
    implementing classes could not access them properly.
    
    So Java kept interface methods:
    
    public
    abstract
    
    by default.



15) Is it mandatory for an abstract class to contain abstract methods?
-->No.
    
    An abstract class may contain:
    
    only normal methods
    no abstract methods
    
    Example:
    
    abstract class Demo {
    
        void show() {
            System.out.println("Hello");
        }
    }
    
    Still object creation is not allowed because class is declared abstract.



16) Why can’t a method in Java be declared as both abstract and synchronized at the same time? Explain logically.
-->Abstract method:
    has no body
    Synchronized method:
    requires method body for thread locking mechanism
    
    Example:
    
    synchronized void show() {
    }
    
    Since abstract methods do not have implementation, synchronization cannot be applied.
    
    So this is invalid:
    
    abstract synchronized void show(); // ERROR
    
    Because:
    
    abstract → no body
    synchronized → needs body
    
    Both contradict each other.
